Perfect! Now I found the test case `testChainedRemoveAttributes`. Let me analyze the problem:

The test is trying to chain multiple `removeAttr` calls on an Element, and it expects that calling `removeAttr` on non-existent attributes doesn't cause issues. Looking at the test:

```java
@Test
public void testChainedRemoveAttributes() {
    String html = "<a one two three four>Text</a>";
    Document doc = Jsoup.parse(html);
    Element a = doc.select("a").first();
    a
        .removeAttr("zero")  // Attribute doesn't exist
        .removeAttr("one")   // Attribute exists
        .removeAttr("two")   // Attribute exists
        .removeAttr("three") // Attribute exists
        .removeAttr("four")  // Attribute exists
        .removeAttr("five"); // Attribute doesn't exist
    assertEquals("<a>Text</a>", a.outerHtml());
}
```

The issue is likely that when calling `removeAttr("zero")` on an element that doesn't have this attribute, the method probably returns `null` or doesn't return the element itself, which would break the method chaining.

Let me check the `removeAttr` method implementation in the Element class:

